recalls.Summary: Mitsubishi Motors North America, Inc. (Mitsubishi) is recalling certain 2004-2006 Lancer and Lancer Evolution vehicles and 2004 Lancer Sportback vehicles.  These vehicles are equipped with a passenger side frontal air bag that may be susceptible to moisture intrusion which, over time, could cause the inflator to rupture.
recalls.Consequence: In the event of a crash necessitating deployment of the passenger's frontal air bag, the inflator could rupture with metal fragments striking the vehicle occupants potentially resulting in serious injury or death.
recalls.Remedy: Mitsubishi will notify owners, and dealers will replace the front passenger air bag inflator with a different inflator, free of charge.  The recall began on October 12, 2017.  Owners may contact Mitsubishi customer service at 1-888-648-7820.  Mitsubishi's number for this recall is SR-17-001.  Note: This recall supersedes recall 15V-321.
recalls.Notes: Owners may also contact the National Highway Traffic Safety Administration Vehicle Safety Hotline at 1-888-327-4236 (TTY 1-800-424-9153), or go to www.safercar.gov.

recalls.Summary: Mitsubishi Motors North America, Inc. (MMNA) is recalling certain 2004-2006 Mitsubishi Lancer vehicles that previously received a like-for-like passenger side frontal air bag inflator under recall 15V321 as interim remedy.  Also recalled are 2004-2006 Lancer vehicles located in Guam or Saipan that previously received or never received a new inflator under 15V321 or 17V569.  These passenger side frontal air bag inflators may be susceptible to moisture intrusion which, over time, could cause the inflator to explode in the event of an air bag deployment.
recalls.Consequence: In the event of a crash necessitating deployment of the passenger's frontal air bag, the inflator could explode with metal fragments striking the vehicle occupants potentially resulting in serious injury or death.
recalls.Remedy: MMNA will notify owners, and dealers will install a final replacement passenger side frontal air bag inflator, free of charge.  The recall began on April 26, 2018.  Owners may contact MMNA customer service at 1-888-648-7820.  MMNA's number for this recall is SR-18-005.
recalls.Notes: Owners may also contact the National Highway Traffic Safety Administration Vehicle Safety Hotline at 1-888-327-4236 (TTY 1-800-424-9153), or go to www.safercar.gov.

recalls.Summary: Mitsubishi Motors North America, Inc. (MMNA) is recalling certain model year 2002-2007 Lancer, 2004 Lancer Wagon, 2003-2006 Lancer Evolution, 2003-2006 Outlander and 2007-2013 Outlander V-6 vehicles originally sold in, or ever registered in, Connecticut, Delaware, Illinois, Indiana, Iowa, Kentucky, Maine, Maryland, Massachusetts, Michigan, Minnesota, Missouri, New Hampshire, New Jersey, New York, Ohio, Pennsylvania, Rhode Island, Vermont, Virginia, West Virginia, Wisconsin and the District of Columbia.  In the affected vehicles, the front lower control arms may detach due to the front cross member corroding from salt water exposure such as from road salt use.
recalls.Consequence: A detached front control arm can result in the loss of control of the vehicle, increasing the risk of a crash.
recalls.Remedy: MMNA will notify owners, and dealers will inspect the front cross members.  Depending on the level of existing corrosion, either a sealing/anti-corrosion agent will be applied or the front cross member will be replaced with a new one that has a sealing/anti-corrosion agent applied to it.  These repairs will be performed free of charge.  The recall began January 2017.  Owners may contact MMNA customer service at 1-888-648-7820.  MMNA's number for this recall is SR-16-003.
recalls.Notes: Owners may also contact the National Highway Traffic Safety Administration Vehicle Safety Hotline at 1-888-327-4236 (TTY 1-800-424-9153), or go to www.safercar.gov.

recalls.Summary: DOPE, INC. IS RECALLING 42,540 COMBINATION CORNER AND BUMPER LAMP ASSEMBLIES OF VARIOUS PART NUMBERS SOLD FOR USE AS AFTERMARKET EQUIPMENT FOR VARIOUS PASSENGER VEHICLES.  THESE HEADLAMPS FAIL TO CONFORM TO THE REQUIREMENTS OF FEDERAL MOTOR VEHICLE SAFETY STANDARD NO. 108, "LAMPS, REFLECTIVE DEVICES, AND ASSOCIATED EQUIPMENT."  THESE LAMPS DO NOT CONTAIN THE REQUIRED AMBER SIDE REFLECTORS.
recalls.Consequence: DECREASED LIGHTING VISIBILITY MAY RESULT IN A VEHICLE CRASH.
recalls.Remedy: DOPE, INC. WILL NOTIFY OWNERS AND OFFER A FULL REFUND FOR THE NONCOMPLIANT COMBINATION LAMPS.  THE SAFETY RECALL BEGAN ON JULY 28, 2009.  OWNERS MAY CONTACT DOPE, INC. AT 1-626-272-1798.
recalls.Notes: THIS RECALL ONLY PERTAINS TO AFTERMARKET REPLACEMENT EQUIPMENT AND HAS NO RELATION TO ANY ORIGINAL EQUIPMENT INSTALLED ON VEHICLES PRODUCED BY THE VEHICLE MANUFACTURER. IN ORDER TO DETERMINE IF YOUR AFTERMARKET LAMP ASSEMBLY IS AFFECTED BY THIS NONCOMPLIANCE, PLEASE REVIEW THE LIST OF MODEL NUMBERS PROVIDED TO US BY DOPE, INC. THE LIST CAN BE FOUND UNDER "DOCUMENT SEARCH" LOCATED AT THE BOTTOM OF YOUR SCREEN. OWNERS MAY ALSO CONTACT THE NATIONAL HIGHWAY TRAFFIC SAFETY ADMINISTRATION'S VEHICLE SAFETY HOTLINE AT 1-888-327-4236 (TTY 1-800-424-9153), OR GO TO HTTP://WWW.SAFERCAR.GOV .

complaints.summary: The steering column on my 2005 Mitsubishi Lancer ES detached while driving. The entire column dropped down from its mounting brackets, causing loss of control. This is a serious safety hazard. The mount bolts were intact previously, but they came loose or the bracket failed without warning. This could have resulted in a crash and severe injury. I believe this may be a structural or manufacturing defect and could affect other Lancer vehicles of similar year. I performed a temporary repair myself so the vehicle could be moved safely, but this does NOT solve the underlying problem. The original steering column mounting should not have failed under normal use.

issues.title: Transfer Case Failure
issues.description: The Active Yaw Control (AYC) transfer case is prone to failure due to inadequate lubrication and bearing wear. This results in complete loss of rear wheel drive, making the vehicle front-wheel drive only.
symptoms: Metallic debris in transfer case oil
issues.fix_description: Replace transfer case assembly, install updated bearings and seals, use proper differential oil
issues.prevention: Regular transfer case oil changes every 15,000 miles, avoid aggressive launches

issues.title: Turbocharger Failure
issues.description: The TD05HR-16G6 turbocharger experiences shaft play and bearing failure, often due to oil starvation or contaminated oil. Common on modified vehicles or those with poor maintenance.
issues.fix_description: Replace or rebuild turbocharger, replace oil lines, check oil pump pressure
issues.prevention: Regular oil changes every 3,000 miles, proper warm-up and cool-down procedures

issues.title: Clutch Master Cylinder Failure
issues.description: The clutch master cylinder develops internal leaks, causing clutch pedal to go to floor and inability to shift gears. Common failure point on high-mileage vehicles.
issues.fix_description: Replace clutch master cylinder and slave cylinder, bleed hydraulic system
issues.prevention: Regular clutch fluid changes, avoid riding the clutch

issues.title: Engine Mount Failure
issues.description: Engine mounts, particularly the upper mount, fail due to the high torque output and aggressive driving. Causes excessive engine movement and vibration.
issues.fix_description: Replace worn engine mounts with OEM or upgraded aftermarket units
issues.prevention: Avoid excessive engine revving and hard launches

issues.title: Fuel Pump Failure
issues.description: In-tank fuel pump fails due to ethanol fuel damage or overheating from running low on fuel. Results in fuel starvation and potential engine damage.
issues.fix_description: Replace fuel pump assembly, clean fuel tank if contaminated
issues.prevention: Keep fuel tank above 1/4 full, use quality fuel with ethanol treatment

issues.title: Timing Belt Failure
issues.description: The 4G63 engine uses an interference design. If the timing belt fails, valves contact pistons causing catastrophic engine damage. Belt tensioner pulley is also prone to failure.
issues.fix_description: Replace timing belt, tensioner, and water pump preventively every 60,000 miles
issues.prevention: Follow maintenance schedule religiously, replace at 60K mile intervals

issues.title: Wheel Speed Sensor Failure
issues.description: ABS wheel speed sensors fail due to corrosion and debris buildup, causing ABS and traction control malfunctions. Common on vehicles driven in harsh conditions.
issues.fix_description: Replace faulty wheel speed sensor, clean sensor mounting area
issues.prevention: Regular cleaning of wheel wells, avoid deep water and salt exposure

issues.title: Intercooler Boost Leak
issues.description: Intercooler piping and couplers develop cracks or become loose, causing boost pressure loss and reduced performance. Plastic intercooler end tanks can crack.
issues.fix_description: Replace cracked intercooler, tighten loose couplers, pressure test boost system
issues.prevention: Regular inspection of intercooler piping, avoid over-boosting

issues.title: Rear Differential Mount Failure
issues.description: The rear differential mount deteriorates from aggressive driving and high torque loads, causing clunking noises and drivetrain vibration.
issues.fix_description: Replace rear differential mount with OEM or upgraded polyurethane unit
issues.prevention: Avoid hard launches and aggressive driving on uneven surfaces

issues.title: Knock Sensor Failure
issues.description: Engine knock sensor fails, preventing proper ignition timing adjustment and potentially allowing engine knock damage. Sensor becomes less sensitive over time.
issues.fix_description: Replace knock sensor and wiring harness if corroded
issues.prevention: Use premium fuel, avoid engine modifications without proper tuning

issues.title: Mass Airflow Sensor Contamination
issues.description: MAF sensor becomes contaminated with oil and debris from modified intake systems or dirty air filters, causing incorrect air/fuel mixture calculations.
issues.fix_description: Clean MAF sensor with appropriate cleaner or replace if damaged
issues.prevention: Regular air filter changes, avoid over-oiling performance air filters

issues.title: Window Regulator Failure
issues.description: Power window regulators fail, particularly on the driver's side, due to worn plastic components and cable stretching. Window drops into door or operates slowly.
issues.fix_description: Replace window regulator assembly and motor if necessary
issues.prevention: Avoid forcing windows when frozen, regular lubrication of window tracks

editorial.tagline: The final evolution of rally-bred perfection
editorial.hero_blurb: The Evo IX represents the culmination of Mitsubishi's rally-bred engineering prowess. With its legendary 4G63T engine and precision all-wheel-drive system, this is where raw performance meets surgical handling dynamics.
editorial.essence: The Evo IX is the ultimate expression of Mitsubishi's WRC-derived technology, combining a bulletproof turbocharged engine with one of the most sophisticated AWD systems ever created. It's a precision instrument disguised as a sedan, built for those who understand that true performance comes from engineering excellence.
editorial.heritage: Born from Mitsubishi's World Rally Championship dominance, the Lancer Evolution lineage spans nine generations of relentless development. The IX marks the final iteration of the original Evo platform before a complete redesign, representing 14 years of continuous refinement.
editorial.design_philosophy: Pure function over form - every element serves performance. Aggressive aerodynamics, massive cooling vents, and a purposeful stance that announces serious intent while maintaining surprising daily usability.
editorial.motorsport_history: Direct descendant of Mitsubishi's WRC championship cars, with technology proven on the world's most demanding rally stages. The Evo's rally DNA runs through every component, from the AWD system to the transmission ratios.
editorial.engine_character: The legendary 4G63T delivers explosive power with a distinctive turbo surge that builds relentlessly from 3,000 RPM. It's an engine that rewards commitment, with massive tuning potential and unbreakable internals.
editorial.transmission_feel: The 5-speed manual is precise and mechanical, with short throws and positive engagement. Each shift feels purposeful, connecting you directly to the drivetrain's sophisticated symphony.
editorial.chassis_dynamics: Razor-sharp handling with incredible neutrality through corners. The active differential works invisibly to rotate the car with throttle inputs, creating an almost telepathic connection between driver and machine.
editorial.steering_feel: Heavy, communicative steering that loads up progressively through corners. Every surface imperfection and traction change is telegraphed directly to your palms with unfiltered honesty.
editorial.brake_confidence: Brembo anchors provide massive stopping power with excellent pedal feel. The system inspires confidence on both street and track, with impressive fade resistance under hard use.
editorial.sound_signature: A distinctive turbocharged growl with wastegate chatter and BOV whooshes. The exhaust note is purposeful rather than melodic - a mechanical soundtrack for serious driving.
editorial.ideal_owner: Driving purists who prioritize performance over comfort, understand mechanical sympathy, and appreciate engineering excellence over luxury appointments.
editorial.not_ideal_for: Comfort-seekers, those wanting luxury features, or drivers who prefer effortless power delivery over engaging mechanical character.
editorial.buyers_summary: Find the cleanest, lowest-mileage example possible - these are appreciating assets now. Verify maintenance history and check for modifications, as many have been heavily modified or tracked.

expertReviews.title: 2006 Mitsubishi Lancer Evo IX GSR Review - Still Relevant?
pros: Exceptional all-wheel drive system with clever ACD technology
Excellent steering feel and feedback through hydraulic steering
Outstanding handling and cornering capability with minimal understeer
Short close-ratio gearing perfect for performance driving
Lightweight feel despite 3,300 lb weight
Strong turbo engine with 287 hp from 2.0L 4-cylinder
cons: Degraded brake performance needs maintenance
Very basic economy car interior quality
Harsh suspension ride quality
High asking price of $30-35k for 20-year-old car
Turbo lag present
Poor fuel economy with engine spinning 4000 RPM at 80 mph
expertReviews.verdict: The Evo IX GSR remains a shockingly good driving experience even by modern standards. Despite its bargain basement interior and high price, it delivers exceptional value from a pure driving pleasure perspective. The clever all-wheel drive system, outstanding handling, and rally car DNA make it one of the best AWD cars available, earning a place alongside the R35 GTR and GR Corolla in the reviewer's top rankings.

Excellent visibility all around

Recaro seats with aggressive bolsters for good support
cons: Very heavy clutch
Uncomfortable seats with minimal cushioning
Hard interior plastics throughout
Noisy cabin with road and gear whine
Boost gauge poorly positioned below AC controls
Slower steering rack requiring more arm movement
Rough ride quality not suitable for daily driving
expertReviews.verdict: The 2006 Mitsubishi Lancer Evolution IX MR is a purpose-built street-legal race car that excels at performance driving but sacrifices comfort. With 286 horsepower from its 2.0L turbo engine, it delivers thrilling acceleration and exceptional handling, though the reviewer notes the STI as a more well-rounded daily driver option. This particular example's stock condition makes it especially valuable for enthusiasts.

expertReviews.title: 2006 Mitsubishi Lancer Evolution IX GSR vs 2023 Toyota GR Corolla Comparison
pros: Immediate front-end response and eager turn-in
Short gear ratios keep engine in power band
Confidence inspiring rally car feel
Easy heel-toe shifting with good ergonomics
Lighter feeling despite 3,300 lb weight
Quick and light hydraulic steering with decent feedback
cons: Budget Megan Racing coilovers are under-damped and bouncy
Brake fade issues despite StopTech upgrades
Very bare bones interior with cheap plastics
Upright and high seating position
No active yaw control (AYC) on US models
Suspension struggles with road undulations
expertReviews.verdict: The Evo IX GSR still embodies the ultimate rally car for the road spirit better than modern alternatives. Despite being two decades old, it offers more immediate fun factor and driver engagement than the technically superior GR Corolla. The Evo's short gearing, quick steering, and eager chassis make it feel lighter and more nimble than its 3,300 lb weight suggests. While the GR Corolla is more competent overall, the Evo puts a bigger smile on the driver's face and ranks among the top all-wheel drive Japanese cars alongside the GTR.

expertReviews.title: Evo IX Review | The Perfect Daily?
pros: Smooth turbo progression starting at 3000 RPM
Predictable and confidence inspiring power delivery
Comfortable stock Recaro seats
Solid six-speed transmission
Powerful Brembo brakes
Makes power easily with bolt-ons
cons: Heavy clutch that takes getting used to
Steering rack requires more effort to turn
Some brake dead spot/numbness
Known reliability issues despite easy power gains
Unused gauge space that could be boost gauge
expertReviews.verdict: The 2006 Evo IX with its 2.0L 4G63 turbo engine delivers smooth, predictable power that's more confidence inspiring than the competing STI. With comfortable seats and solid build quality, it makes an excellent daily driver rally car despite some minor ergonomic issues. The reviewer was impressed by how well the nearly stock example performed.
